1
00:00:00,640 --> 00:00:02,399
The cozy English.

2
00:00:02,399 --> 00:00:04,160
Learn English slowly.

3
00:00:04,160 --> 00:00:11,779
Close your eyes for a moment, or just let your gaze soften on something still.

4
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:13,940
Welcome back to the cozy English.

5
00:00:14,355 --> 00:00:18,475
I'm Emma, and as I was walking to the studio this morning,

6
00:00:18,595 --> 00:00:22,875
I noticed how the light was catching the dust motes in the air,

7
00:00:22,995 --> 00:00:26,795
just tiny golden specks dancing in the sun.

8
00:00:27,749 --> 00:00:34,589
It reminded me that even the air we breathe is full of little movements we usually ignore.

9
00:00:35,269 --> 00:00:43,355
I decided right then to let today be whatever it needs to be without forcing a perfect plan.

10
00:00:43,955 --> 00:00:51,115
I'm just here in this chair with my favorite mug and a very quiet heart.

11
00:00:51,395 --> 00:00:55,195
Hi, Emma, and hello to everyone joining our circle today.

12
00:00:55,840 --> 00:00:57,720
It's funny you say that.

13
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:03,560
I'm sitting here across from you, and I can feel that stillness you're talking about.

14
00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:08,280
Usually, my mind is a checklist of things I haven't done yet,

15
00:01:08,695 --> 00:01:14,815
but today, I'm trying to just listen to the sound of the city outside the window,

16
00:01:15,095 --> 00:01:19,214
that distant that usually feels like pressure,

17
00:01:19,415 --> 00:01:22,574
but today just feels like a lullaby.

18
00:01:23,990 --> 00:01:29,229
It's nice to just breathe for a second before we dive into our thoughts.

19
00:01:29,510 --> 00:01:31,070
It really is.

20
00:01:31,670 --> 00:01:35,869
But I have to be honest with you, Daniel, and with everyone listening.

21
00:01:36,315 --> 00:01:39,714
This stillness is something I've had to fight for.

22
00:01:40,394 --> 00:01:44,914
For years, I used to hide in the editing phase of my life.

23
00:01:45,195 --> 00:01:47,454
I would record a podcast episode

24
00:01:47,454 --> 00:01:51,789
or write a lesson and then obsess over it for weeks,

25
00:01:51,990 --> 00:01:57,870
convinced that if I just changed one more word, it would finally be ready.

26
00:01:58,390 --> 00:02:03,390
I told myself I was being a professional, but really, I was just terrified.

27
00:02:04,115 --> 00:02:07,515
That sounds exactly like where I am right now.

28
00:02:07,955 --> 00:02:14,075
I spent the last three hours trying to edit a single image for our community post.

29
00:02:14,355 --> 00:02:21,370
I kept changing the font, moving the logo by one millimeter, then changing it back.

30
00:02:22,130 --> 00:02:28,170
Every time I thought I was finished, a little voice said, it's not quite right yet.

31
00:02:28,545 --> 00:02:32,825
If you post this, people will think you don't care.

32
00:02:33,665 --> 00:02:37,145
So I just didn't post it.

33
00:02:37,665 --> 00:02:46,200
I've been sitting in this calm studio, but my brain is exhausted from a battle over one millimeter.

34
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:52,200
That little voice is the architect of what I call the golden cage of excellence.

35
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:59,405
We tell ourselves that our perfectionism is a virtue, that it shows how much we care about quality.

36
00:02:59,925 --> 00:03:04,205
But if we look closer, that cage is built out of fear.

37
00:03:04,645 --> 00:03:11,405
We stay inside the polishing phase because as long as the work isn't done, it can't be judged.

38
00:03:12,100 --> 00:03:16,700
Perfectionism is often just procrastination in a fancy suit.

39
00:03:16,980 --> 00:03:21,180
It feels like excellence, but it functions like a prison.

40
00:03:21,460 --> 00:03:24,555
Procrastination in a fancy suit.

41
00:03:25,075 --> 00:03:28,075
That's a painful realization.

42
00:03:28,915 --> 00:03:37,835
I've always been proud of my high standards, thinking that by being my own harshest critic, I was ensuring quality.

43
00:03:38,860 --> 00:03:40,340
But you're right.

44
00:03:40,460 --> 00:03:42,900
I'm not producing quality.

45
00:03:43,340 --> 00:03:46,260
I'm just producing silence.

46
00:03:47,180 --> 00:03:50,660
I feel like if I speak English with a mistake

47
00:03:50,705 --> 00:03:52,564
or if I post a design

48
00:03:52,564 --> 00:03:56,665
that isn't 100% perfect, I'm failing.

49
00:03:57,344 --> 00:04:04,104
But the result of trying to be 100% perfect is that I'm 0% finished.

50
00:04:04,859 --> 00:04:11,620
Is my excellence actually just a way to avoid the vulnerability of being seen?

51
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:13,060
Exactly.

52
00:04:13,660 --> 00:04:16,739
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it,

53
00:04:17,094 --> 00:04:24,175
and your energy is much better spent on connecting with people than on moving a logo by a millimeter.

54
00:04:24,775 --> 00:04:28,315
A private life is a happy life means realizing

55
00:04:28,315 --> 00:04:30,155
that the perfect version of you

56
00:04:30,155 --> 00:04:35,890
that the world sees is often the most lonely and exhausted version of you.

57
00:04:36,409 --> 00:04:43,169
The beauty of life happens in the messy parts, the parts we try to hide because they aren't perfect yet.

58
00:04:43,815 --> 00:04:48,015
I think I'm ready to take off the fancy suit, Emma.

59
00:04:48,455 --> 00:04:52,015
I'm tired of being perfectly silent.

60
00:04:52,455 --> 00:04:55,695
I want to be imperfectly active.

61
00:04:56,840 --> 00:05:02,080
Before we move on, I want to invite everyone to join us in this journey.

62
00:05:02,599 --> 00:05:07,840
If you find these conversations helpful, please hit that subscribe button.

63
00:05:08,039 --> 00:05:11,760
It helps us keep the lights on in this cozy corner.

64
00:05:12,224 --> 00:05:16,005
And for those of you who want to really sit with these ideas

65
00:05:16,005 --> 00:05:18,265
and study the language we use,

66
00:05:18,385 --> 00:05:22,265
you can download the full PDF script in the description.

67
00:05:22,705 --> 00:05:27,545
It's a great way to follow along without the pressure of being perfect at listening.

68
00:05:28,719 --> 00:05:32,600
Now I want you to ask yourself a hard question.

69
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:37,320
What is the thing you are currently pretending to improve

70
00:05:37,359 --> 00:05:42,840
or perfect, but in reality, are just avoiding the fear of finishing it?

71
00:05:43,155 --> 00:05:49,755
So, Emma, if I take off this fancy suit of perfectionism, what am I left with?

72
00:05:49,794 --> 00:05:54,535
The idea of good enough honestly feels a bit dangerous to me.

73
00:05:54,535 --> 00:05:57,895
If I settle for good enough in my English studies

74
00:05:57,895 --> 00:06:02,770
or my work, doesn't that lead to a slippery slope of mediocrity?

75
00:06:02,890 --> 00:06:08,050
I've always been taught that if a job is worth doing, it's worth doing right.

76
00:06:08,250 --> 00:06:14,370
If I start accepting 80% effort, I'm worried that I'll eventually stop caring altogether.

77
00:06:15,145 --> 00:06:21,185
How do you distinguish between being healthy with your standards and just being lazy?

78
00:06:21,465 --> 00:06:28,385
That's a fair concern, but there's a massive difference between good enough and lazy.

79
00:06:29,210 --> 00:06:32,290
Lazy is not caring about the result.

80
00:06:32,650 --> 00:06:40,850
Good enough is caring so much about the outcome that you refuse to let perfectionism stop you from reaching it.

81
00:06:41,495 --> 00:06:45,775
Think about the Pareto principle or the eighty twenty rule.

82
00:06:46,135 --> 00:06:52,255
Often, 80% of your results come from just 20% of your effort.

83
00:06:52,694 --> 00:07:01,790
The last 20% of perfection takes an enormous amount of energy, but adds very little real value.

84
00:07:02,629 --> 00:07:10,585
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it, and usually, useful beats flawless.

85
00:07:11,104 --> 00:07:13,545
Useful beats flawless.

86
00:07:13,745 --> 00:07:17,225
I like the sound of that, but it's hard to trust.

87
00:07:17,424 --> 00:07:22,505
I feel like my high standards are a shield that protects me from criticism.

88
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:28,080
If I'm perfect, nobody can hurt my feelings or tell me I'm wrong.

89
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:34,080
But that shield is heavy, Daniel, and it doesn't actually work.

90
00:07:34,599 --> 00:07:36,560
Let me give you a real example.

91
00:07:37,515 --> 00:07:41,375
Last month, you needed to ask that guest speaker for an interview.

92
00:07:41,375 --> 00:07:42,115
Right?

93
00:07:42,315 --> 00:07:46,515
You were overthinking that email for three days.

94
00:07:46,875 --> 00:07:52,995
Finally, you just got tired, typed a quick message with a couple of typos, and hit send.

95
00:07:53,489 --> 00:07:55,450
It wasn't impressive.

96
00:07:55,650 --> 00:07:58,330
It was just understandable.

97
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:00,250
And what happened?

98
00:08:00,289 --> 00:08:03,770
He replied in five minutes and said yes.

99
00:08:03,890 --> 00:08:06,010
He didn't even mention the typos.

100
00:08:06,375 --> 00:08:10,975
He just cared that the message was clear and that I was respectful.

101
00:08:11,414 --> 00:08:16,415
I guess the flawless version wouldn't have gotten a different result.

102
00:08:16,375 --> 00:08:19,915
It just would have taken me three days longer to get it.

103
00:08:19,915 --> 00:08:20,815
Exactly.

104
00:08:21,439 --> 00:08:24,120
That is a good enough win.

105
00:08:24,479 --> 00:08:32,200
A private life is a happy life means your standards should be for you, not for a performance.

106
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:39,145
When you aim for good enough, you give yourself the freedom to actually communicate.

107
00:08:39,664 --> 00:08:45,785
If you're afraid to make a mistake, you'll never say anything interesting in a new language.

108
00:08:46,065 --> 00:08:49,785
You'll just say the safe things you know are perfect.

109
00:08:50,840 --> 00:08:57,760
Remember, understandable beats impressive every single time in the real world.

110
00:08:57,800 --> 00:08:59,840
It's a shift in perspective.

111
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:07,375
Instead of seeing good enough as a failure of quality, I should see it as a victory of momentum.

112
00:09:07,735 --> 00:09:15,935
I'd rather have 10 good conversations in English than one perfect sentence that I was too afraid to even say.

113
00:09:16,310 --> 00:09:20,270
Let's try a mini exercise for everyone listening.

114
00:09:20,870 --> 00:09:23,150
Stop for a second and think.

115
00:09:23,669 --> 00:09:27,070
What is one thing in your life right now?

116
00:09:27,270 --> 00:09:37,095
Maybe a study task, a chore, or a message, where 80% effort already gives you 90% of the value.

117
00:09:37,775 --> 00:09:44,055
What is the one thing where being useful is actually better than being flawless?

118
00:09:44,819 --> 00:09:47,580
I'm thinking of my vocabulary list.

119
00:09:47,780 --> 00:09:50,540
I've been trying to memorize the dictionary,

120
00:09:50,579 --> 00:09:57,900
but really, knowing the most common 500 words is what gives me almost all my value in conversation.

121
00:09:58,545 --> 00:10:01,865
Everything else is just over polishing.

122
00:10:02,064 --> 00:10:04,665
That's a perfect realization.

123
00:10:05,345 --> 00:10:13,305
But even when we know this, there is still a hidden cost to waiting that most people never calculate.

124
00:10:13,799 --> 00:10:19,280
You mentioned a hidden cost earlier, and I've been sitting here trying to calculate it in my head.

125
00:10:19,640 --> 00:10:25,280
If I spend an extra week perfecting a project, I'm losing seven days of my life.

126
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:28,080
But it's more than just time, isn't it?

127
00:10:28,584 --> 00:10:33,585
It's the things I didn't do because I was so focused on this one thing.

128
00:10:34,025 --> 00:10:38,525
While I've been obsessing over the perfect way to introduce this podcast

129
00:10:38,525 --> 00:10:41,665
or the perfect way to explain a grammar point,

130
00:10:41,840 --> 00:10:47,080
I've missed out on dozens of other opportunities to connect with our listeners.

131
00:10:47,439 --> 00:10:54,040
It's like I'm paying a massive tax on my potential just to avoid a tiny bit of embarrassment.

132
00:10:54,905 --> 00:10:59,425
That is exactly what economists call opportunity cost.

133
00:11:00,025 --> 00:11:07,905
Every hour you spend over polishing a single sentence is an hour you aren't spending on a new idea,

134
00:11:08,025 --> 00:11:11,310
a new conversation, or even just resting

135
00:11:11,310 --> 00:11:13,730
so you can be creative tomorrow.

136
00:11:14,250 --> 00:11:19,090
The world is moving at an incredible pace in 2026.

137
00:11:19,449 --> 00:11:26,945
If you wait until you are 100% ready, the opportunity will have already passed you by.

138
00:11:27,225 --> 00:11:34,865
The market will have changed, the conversation will have moved on, and your perfect work will be irrelevant.

139
00:11:35,870 --> 00:11:41,189
In the digital age, speed is often a higher quality than perfection.

140
00:11:41,630 --> 00:11:44,390
That feels very stressful, Emma.

141
00:11:44,349 --> 00:11:49,030
It sounds like you're telling me to just rush everything so I don't miss out.

142
00:11:49,755 --> 00:11:57,475
If I'm always worried about the opportunity cost, aren't I just trading one type of anxiety for another?

143
00:11:57,755 --> 00:12:03,235
Now, instead of worrying about quality, I'm worrying about being too slow.

144
00:12:04,030 --> 00:12:11,670
I don't want my life to feel like a race where I'm just throwing good enough things out the window as I drive past.

145
00:12:12,109 --> 00:12:15,750
I want to feel like I'm building something that lasts.

146
00:12:16,109 --> 00:12:17,590
It's not about rushing.

147
00:12:17,924 --> 00:12:20,445
It's about effective momentum.

148
00:12:20,885 --> 00:12:22,605
Think of it like a train.

149
00:12:23,125 --> 00:12:26,605
It takes a lot of energy to get the train moving,

150
00:12:26,804 --> 00:12:30,925
but once it's at cruising speed, it's much easier to maintain.

151
00:12:32,089 --> 00:12:38,290
Perfectionism is like slamming on the brakes every five meters to check if the wheels are shiny.

152
00:12:38,569 --> 00:12:40,850
You never get to the destination.

153
00:12:41,609 --> 00:12:44,850
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it,

154
00:12:45,295 --> 00:12:51,095
and the momentum of your growth is worth much more than the polish on a single project.

155
00:12:51,535 --> 00:12:54,055
A private life is a happy life,

156
00:12:54,175 --> 00:13:01,340
means you don't need the external validation of a perfect score to know you are moving in the right direction.

157
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:09,900
So the cost of waiting is that I'm essentially staying at the station while everyone else's train has already left.

158
00:13:10,915 --> 00:13:18,795
I'm starting to see that my fear of being wrong is actually a fear of being seen in progress.

159
00:13:19,235 --> 00:13:25,275
I want to arrive at the destination without anyone seeing me do the hard work of travelling.

160
00:13:25,939 --> 00:13:30,620
I want the perfect result without the messy journey.

161
00:13:31,140 --> 00:13:36,620
But if I don't accept the mess, I never actually leave the station.

162
00:13:37,140 --> 00:13:37,900
Exactly.

163
00:13:38,594 --> 00:13:43,674
We all want the highlight reel, but life happens in the raw footage.

164
00:13:44,275 --> 00:13:48,475
The messy middle is where the actual transformation occurs.

165
00:13:48,914 --> 00:13:50,535
It's where you make the mistakes

166
00:13:50,535 --> 00:13:58,860
that teach you the most, and where you find the creative solutions you never would have found if you were just following a perfect plan.

167
00:13:59,140 --> 00:14:04,540
The messy middle sounds like a place I've been trying to avoid my whole life.

168
00:14:05,215 --> 00:14:08,055
It sounds uncomfortable.

169
00:14:08,415 --> 00:14:15,495
It is uncomfortable, but it's also the only place where you are truly alive and growing.

170
00:14:16,334 --> 00:14:18,135
The messy middle.

171
00:14:18,670 --> 00:14:21,990
Honestly, Emma, that sounds like my worst nightmare.

172
00:14:22,030 --> 00:14:25,350
My brain is wired to love the beginning,

173
00:14:25,310 --> 00:14:27,270
the excitement of a new project,

174
00:14:27,310 --> 00:14:31,190
and the end where everything is clean and finished.

175
00:14:31,310 --> 00:14:32,310
But the middle?

176
00:14:32,574 --> 00:14:35,315
That's where the English grammar gets confusing.

177
00:14:35,315 --> 00:14:41,415
The design looks amateur, and the original vision feels like it's falling apart.

178
00:14:41,775 --> 00:14:47,335
I usually stop right there because I assume the mess is a sign that I've failed.

179
00:14:47,579 --> 00:14:52,660
I tell myself, if I were really good at this, it wouldn't look this bad.

180
00:14:53,100 --> 00:14:59,060
Is the mess really a necessary part of the path, or am I just doing it wrong?

181
00:14:59,515 --> 00:15:03,795
The mess is the most honest part of the path, Daniel.

182
00:15:04,234 --> 00:15:08,915
Every great masterpiece looks like a disaster halfway through.

183
00:15:09,435 --> 00:15:12,114
A half painted portrait looks like a ghost.

184
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:16,760
A half built house is just a pile of bricks and dust.

185
00:15:17,280 --> 00:15:22,280
We've been conditioned by social media to see only the finished product,

186
00:15:22,479 --> 00:15:25,640
so we think the ugly phase is a mistake.

187
00:15:26,485 --> 00:15:29,885
But the middle is where the real work happens.

188
00:15:30,645 --> 00:15:34,205
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it.

189
00:15:34,405 --> 00:15:40,205
And the worth it part of the middle isn't the quality of the work, it's the quality of the effort.

190
00:15:40,970 --> 00:15:48,130
You are training your brain to handle frustration, which is a much more valuable skill than being perfect.

191
00:15:48,410 --> 00:15:51,710
So I shouldn't be judging my progress based on

192
00:15:51,710 --> 00:15:55,090
how pretty the result looks while I'm in the thick of it.

193
00:15:55,574 --> 00:15:57,055
That's hard to do.

194
00:15:57,334 --> 00:16:02,815
When I hear myself struggling to find a word in English, I feel like I'm moving backward.

195
00:16:02,775 --> 00:16:09,295
I feel like I'm losing my identity as a smart person because I'm making stupid mistakes.

196
00:16:10,020 --> 00:16:11,959
I want to skip the mess

197
00:16:11,959 --> 00:16:14,360
and just get to the part where I'm fluent

198
00:16:14,360 --> 00:16:19,879
and confident, but you're saying that the stupidity of the middle is

199
00:16:19,879 --> 00:16:23,179
actually the price of the wisdom at the end.

200
00:16:23,219 --> 00:16:24,220
Precisely.

201
00:16:24,945 --> 00:16:30,825
A private life is a happy life, means you don't have to show anyone your messy middle.

202
00:16:31,185 --> 00:16:36,985
You can be bad at something in private until you are good at it in public.

203
00:16:37,665 --> 00:16:40,185
The mess is your private laboratory.

204
00:16:40,990 --> 00:16:43,830
If you try to make the middle look like the end,

205
00:16:43,790 --> 00:16:47,410
you'll never experiment, you'll never take risks,

206
00:16:47,410 --> 00:16:50,230
and you'll never find your unique voice.

207
00:16:50,670 --> 00:16:54,310
You have to give yourself permission to be ugly for a while.

208
00:16:54,985 --> 00:16:59,505
If you can't handle being a beginner, you'll never become a master.

209
00:16:59,704 --> 00:17:01,745
Permission to be ugly.

210
00:17:02,025 --> 00:17:03,985
I've never given myself that.

211
00:17:04,265 --> 00:17:08,784
I've always demanded that my first draft be a final draft.

212
00:17:09,400 --> 00:17:14,959
I guess that's why I have so many unfinished projects in my drafts folder.

213
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:20,319
I hit the messy middle, got scared by the ugliness, and walked away.

214
00:17:20,840 --> 00:17:23,200
I thought I was protecting my standards,

215
00:17:23,424 --> 00:17:28,824
but I was really just protecting my ego from the reality of hard work.

216
00:17:28,865 --> 00:17:32,904
Your ego is the only thing that's afraid of the mess.

217
00:17:33,105 --> 00:17:35,784
Your potential, however, thrives in it.

218
00:17:36,579 --> 00:17:42,060
The middle is where you find out who you really are when things aren't going perfectly.

219
00:17:42,500 --> 00:17:44,859
It's where resilience is born.

220
00:17:44,900 --> 00:17:46,120
Alright, Emma.

221
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:48,859
I'm ready to stop hiding in the drafts.

222
00:17:48,900 --> 00:17:53,554
I'm ready to embrace the mess and just get the thing done.

223
00:17:53,915 --> 00:17:59,154
But how do I actually hit send when I still feel like it's not ready?

224
00:17:59,195 --> 00:18:03,715
That brings us to our final challenge, the ship it mindset.

225
00:18:04,170 --> 00:18:05,309
Okay, Emma.

226
00:18:05,309 --> 00:18:07,570
I'm standing at the edge of the cliff.

227
00:18:07,850 --> 00:18:10,929
I've accepted that perfection is a cage.

228
00:18:11,209 --> 00:18:16,689
I understand the cost of waiting, and I'm even willing to be ugly in the messy middle.

229
00:18:17,475 --> 00:18:25,675
But there is still that final terrifying moment when my finger is hovering over the send or post button.

230
00:18:26,035 --> 00:18:29,675
That's when the what ifs come back at full volume.

231
00:18:30,579 --> 00:18:32,859
What if I missed a glaring error?

232
00:18:32,820 --> 00:18:34,859
What if I regret it tomorrow?

233
00:18:35,300 --> 00:18:44,540
How do I actually develop the courage to just ship it when every bone in my body is telling me to check it just one more time?

234
00:18:45,355 --> 00:18:49,874
You have to realize that ship it isn't an act of confidence.

235
00:18:49,915 --> 00:18:52,195
It's an act of discipline.

236
00:18:52,155 --> 00:18:58,834
One of the best ways to overcome that final hesitation is to set a nonnegotiable deadline.

237
00:18:59,270 --> 00:19:04,830
Tell yourself, at 4PM, this email goes out no matter what.

238
00:19:05,190 --> 00:19:11,070
By making the time more important than the quality, you take the power away from your inner critic.

239
00:19:11,555 --> 00:19:14,955
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it,

240
00:19:14,915 --> 00:19:16,635
and at the end of a project,

241
00:19:16,595 --> 00:19:21,514
the most worth it thing is the completion, not the perfection.

242
00:19:21,555 --> 00:19:23,834
A nonnegotiable deadline.

243
00:19:24,275 --> 00:19:26,795
That forces the decision out of my hands.

244
00:19:27,610 --> 00:19:29,570
But I know myself, Emma.

245
00:19:29,610 --> 00:19:35,649
I'll hit send and then spend the next hour sweating, wishing I could pull the email back.

246
00:19:36,090 --> 00:19:39,649
I'll probably wake up at 3AM thinking about a typo.

247
00:19:39,855 --> 00:19:42,774
That's why you need the after ship rule.

248
00:19:42,895 --> 00:19:47,895
No editing, no deleting, and no checking for twenty four hours.

249
00:19:48,175 --> 00:19:50,375
Once it's out, it's out.

250
00:19:50,415 --> 00:19:52,294
If you see a mistake later,

251
00:19:52,255 --> 00:19:58,590
consider it your tuition fee, the small price you pay for the lesson of moving forward.

252
00:19:58,950 --> 00:20:00,830
And here is a secret.

253
00:20:01,030 --> 00:20:05,070
If you cringe at what you did tomorrow, congratulations.

254
00:20:05,350 --> 00:20:07,710
That means you are already growing.

255
00:20:08,035 --> 00:20:13,575
You are already a better version of yourself than the person who shipped that work yesterday.

256
00:20:13,575 --> 00:20:16,235
If you cringe, you're growing.

257
00:20:16,835 --> 00:20:18,794
I've never thought of it that way.

258
00:20:19,155 --> 00:20:24,899
I always thought cringing was a sign of failure, but it's actually a sign of progress.

259
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:31,619
I'd rather be an imperfect human who is moving than a perfect ghost who is invisible.

260
00:20:32,220 --> 00:20:38,100
A private life is a happy life means I don't need to perform for the whole world.

261
00:20:38,515 --> 00:20:41,754
I just need to be honest with my own growth.

262
00:20:42,435 --> 00:20:46,875
I'm ready to start shipping, and I'm ready to stop deleting.

263
00:20:46,915 --> 00:20:48,475
That's the spirit.

264
00:20:48,835 --> 00:20:54,075
Most people are so worried about their own mistakes that they won't even notice yours.

265
00:20:54,330 --> 00:20:57,730
They are looking for value, not flaws.

266
00:20:57,930 --> 00:21:02,830
And for our listeners, we want you to join this ship it movement with us.

267
00:21:02,830 --> 00:21:05,730
Here is your cozy English challenge.

268
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:10,050
Pick one thing today that you've been polishing for too long.

269
00:21:10,755 --> 00:21:15,754
Set a ten minute timer, finish it, and hit send or post.

270
00:21:16,115 --> 00:21:18,874
Then, follow the after ship rule.

271
00:21:18,834 --> 00:21:21,274
No deleting for twenty four hours.

272
00:21:21,235 --> 00:21:25,115
Don't forget to download the full PDF script in the description.

273
00:21:25,580 --> 00:21:30,500
It's a tool to help you grow, not a perfect document you need to fear.

274
00:21:30,780 --> 00:21:34,160
Use it to find the phrases that help you speak your truth.

275
00:21:34,160 --> 00:21:36,580
We want to hear from you in the comments.

276
00:21:36,780 --> 00:21:39,540
Don't just tell us, what did you ship today?

277
00:21:40,005 --> 00:21:42,684
Tell us, what did you survive?

278
00:21:43,125 --> 00:21:47,324
What was the fear you walked through to get that task done?

279
00:21:47,605 --> 00:21:51,144
Let's celebrate the survival of our perfectionism together.

280
00:21:51,144 --> 00:21:54,685
Thank you for spending this quiet, imperfect time with us.

281
00:21:55,179 --> 00:21:57,679
We'll be here for you in the next episode.

282
00:21:57,679 --> 00:22:00,179
Take it one hour at a time.

283
00:22:00,299 --> 00:22:01,139
Goodbye.

284
00:22:01,179 --> 00:22:03,200
Goodbye, and stay cozy.
